In 2021, nearly 50% of internships were unpaid, according to a survey by the National Association of Colleges and Employers. These types of internships have proven to further inequity, giving opportunities to a select few while isolating others. So why are unpaid internships still so prevalent in our workforce today? 

Read more: https://cnb.cx/3AKBcBK

node.title: Here's why unpaid internships still exist in corporate America

node.text:
Need advice on how to succeed? Turn off the computer and start reading. 📖⁠
⁠
At the link in bio, business leaders and advisors from The Oracles share 5 books that helped them get ahead in life.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by CNBC Make It on August 18, 2021. May be an image of office and text that says 'How much money a single person needs to earn to get by in every U.S. state #makeit'.

node.text:
For single people living in the U.S., earning enough money to make ends meet looks different for each person. ⁠
⁠
Use MIT's Living Wage Calculator at the link in our bio to see the minimum income necessary for a single person to cover their living expenses and stay above the poverty line, without outside help, across the U.S.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by CNBC Make It on August 18, 2021. May be an image of 4 people, beard, people standing, indoor and text that says 'How 4 college students tried to steal rare books worth millions from a school library 一 and what got them caught ル serie BUILD BUIL BUIL @BU #makeit'.

node.text:
One morning in December 2004, four men embarked on a daring heist. Their target: several volumes of some of the world's rarest books, later valued at more than $5.7 million in total, located in the special collections library at Transylvania University in Lexington, Kentucky. 📚⁠
⁠
But their plan was flawed — and instead, the thieves walked away with a minimal haul, leaving just enough clues to lead the police to their door. At the link in bio, we're breaking down the moment that led to ⁠
"the biggest slip-up in the world."

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by CNBC Make It on August 17, 2021. May be an image of 1 person and text that says '9 habits that can instantly destroy your reputation, according to these self-made millionaires åmakeit'.

node.text:
Many of world's most successful people have one thing in common: an impeccable reputation — which, when you really think about it, isn't easy to develop and maintain.⁠
⁠
At the link in bio, self-made millionaires share 9 bad habits that can quickly put a dent in your reputation.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by CNBC Make It on August 17, 2021. May be an image of 4 people, people standing and text that says 'The 7 common mistakes 'people who are terrible at small talk' always make, according to a public speaking expert #makeit'.

node.text:
Like any other form of public speaking, small talk skills have nothing to do with your personality, and everything to do with learning to empathize with your audience. ⁠
⁠
At the link in bio, we're sharing 7 mistakes that people who are terrible at small talk always make.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by CNBC Make It on August 17, 2021. May be an image of 5 people, child, people standing, road and text that says 'This family traded in their $4,200-a-month mortgage for a $14,000 Rv-and they're never going back #makeit'.

node.text:
It was the end of 2019, and Karen and Sylvester Akpan knew they needed to make some changes. The couple owed over $110,000 collectively in student loan debt and felt like they weren't able to start building wealth for their son, Aiden, now 8.⁠
⁠
At the link in bio, the Akpans explain why they have no intention to move back to a "normal" home any time soon.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by CNBC Make It on August 17, 2021. May be an image of 1 person and text that says '2021 is shaping up to be another tricky tax year-here's here's what you can do to stay prepared #makeit'.

node.text:
A number of factors will make 2021 tax returns more complicated than average, including the third stimulus payment that started going out in March. 😫⁠
⁠
At the link in bio, we're sharing 2 key things you can start doing now so that you are ready when tax day rolls around in 2022. ✍️

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by CNBC Make It on August 16, 2021. May be an image of 1 person and text that says '×I don't wait for those things to find me:' How actress Kristen Bell combats her anxiety and depression at work #makeit'.

node.text:
Kristen Bell has spent the last two decades working in one of the world's most pressure-filled environments. Her biggest lesson for managing anxiety and depression: Don't let things fester.⁠
⁠
Along the way, Bell has picked up a few simple tactics to manage her own mental health. She shared her top three strategies in the link in bio.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by CNBC Make It on August 16, 2021. May be an image of child and text that says 'Educational psychologist: If there's one skill you should teach your kids this is it #makeit'.

node.text:
There are numerous ways to help a child's learning and development, but one leading educational psychologist says unstructured "child-led" play is "intrinsically valuable" to fostering basic skills. ⁠
⁠
Read how it helps children to develop and why you shouldn't be as quick to stop "rough play" at the link in bio.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by CNBC Make It on August 16, 2021. May be an image of 1 person and text that says 'Your first job could significantly impact your heart's health later in life, a new study suggests #makeit'.

node.text:
While your first job as a teen or in your early 20s probably isn't a good predictor of your future success, it could be an indicator of your heart health later in life, a new study suggests. ⁠
⁠
Their findings: participants who were more educated and held managerial positions in their first few jobs had healthier hearts 20 years later than those who didn't.⁠
⁠
At the link in our bio, we're breaking down how researchers came to this conclusion, plus the part of the study that surprised them most.
